The plaintiff seeks an order under the Partition Act, R.S.N.S. 1985 c. 333, for the partition and sale of two properties owned jointly by the parties, a declaration of ownership regarding personal property and a division of other property owned by the defendant based on a constructive trust. That principle is not defeated by the existence of a matrimonial relationship between the parties; but, for the principle to succeed, the facts must display an enrichment, a corresponding deprivation, and the absence of any juristic reason ‑ such as a contract or disposition of law ‑ for the enrichment." (2) For a plaintiff to prove an unjust enrichment, the plaintiff must meet three requirements:



(a) an enrichment;

(b) a corresponding deprivation;

(c) the absence of any juristic reason for the enrichment. In applying this step‑by‑step analysis to this case I find that Mrs. Keddy has met the three requirements to prove an unjust enrichment. CONCLUSION For these reasons the plaintiff shall be entitled to enter judgment against the defendant for the following amounts:

